{"can_edit": true, "from": {"name": "Peter Boyd", "id": "1312089751"}, "revision": "10151881980795019", "updated_time": "2012-06-20T19:29:56+0000", "can_delete": true, "message": "<p>A lot of people here ask questions about different aspects of Linux.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Since answering these questions again and again is a tedious work, i  will try to summarize some of the important topics that may be of  interest to new Linux users...</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>First of all if you decided to test Linux, choose you distro and  download/burn its LiveCD version (if such version is offered). That will  help you in your decision.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Choosing the right distro is usually hard, because you get quite a bunch of opinions which distro is better, which sucks etc...</p>\n<p>But these links may help you choose:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Distrowatch -&gt; http://distrowatch.com/dwres.php?resource=major</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Linux Wizard -&gt; http://www.zegeniestudios.net/ldc/index.php?select_lang=true</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>After you install your distribution and get a bit acquainted with it you may like to have a look at some of the following:</p>\n<p>==============================================================</p>\n<ol><li>Make sure you only add to your repositories <strong>trusted sources</strong> </li>\n<li>Make sure you have activated <strong>all your distro&#039;s security updates</strong> and general updates repositories</li>\n<li>You may add some additional repositories that offer new versions of some packages like KDE, some multimedia programs etc</li>\n</ol><p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Ubuntu family</strong>:</li>\n</ul><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Backports - https://launchpad.net/~kubuntu-ppa and https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Kubuntu</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Medibuntu - http://medibuntu.org/repository.php</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Wine - http://www.winehq.org/download/ubuntu</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 VirtualBox - https://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Linux_Downloads</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Mandriva</strong>: </li>\n</ul><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 The PLF Repos - http://easyurpmi.zarb.org/</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Fedora</strong>:</li>\n</ul><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Read this first -\u00a0http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Third_party_repositories</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 RPM Fusion - http://rpmfusion.org/Configuration</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Linva (Add RPM Fusion FIRST) -\u00a0http://rpm.livna.org/</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul><li><strong>openSuse</strong>:</li>\n</ul><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Read this first -\u00a0http://en.opensuse.org/Package_repositories</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Packman - http://en.opensuse.org/Additional_package_repositories</p>\n<p>\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Note that most repos in SuSE are available under &quot;add repository&quot; and selecting &quot;Community Repository&quot;.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<ul><li>Pardus:</li>\n</ul><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Read this first for installation and more: http://en.pardus-wiki.org/Installation:Contents</p>\n<p>PardusRepo - http://worldforum.pardus-linux.nl/index.php?topic=3478.0 (Second post from Atobloo).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Some security related remarks:</p>\n<p>====================</p>\n<ol><li>Avoid installing unnecessary services. Like if you do not intend  accessing your computer remotely, do not install the SSH server etc</li>\n<li><strong>Never give your root password (or root access) to anyone</strong> you do not entirely trust</li>\n<li><strong>Do not run scripts from unknown sources</strong> especially do not run them  as root. Same goes for installing packages from untrusted sources... </li>\n</ol><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Finally if you feel lost among the pile of applications that Linux offers you, and you need some help in finding alternatives/analogues of  you favorite MS Windows programs.... You may consult the Linux  Alternative Project (formerly the Linux Equivalent Project) -&gt; http://www.linuxalt.com/</p>", "subject": "Linux First Steps and \"Rules\"", "id": "10151881980825019", "icon": "https://s-static.ak.facebook.com/rsrc.php/v2/yi/r/-64q65AWgXb.png"}